<div id="content" class="content wikipage" lang="en" dir="ltr">
<p id="l1">
In typography, the portion of some lowercase letters that extends below the character's <a title="x-Height" href="x-Height">x-height</a>. The descending characters are <em>g</em>, <em>j</em>, <em>p</em>, <em>q</em>, and <strong>'. They may not always align at the bottom of the descender, although most do. One must be careful that line spacing, or <a title="Leading" href="Leading">leading</a>, is sufficient so that the descenders of one line do not touch the <a title="Ascender" href="Ascender">ascender</a>s of the next line. <a title="Typeface" href="Typeface">Typeface</a>s are designed to meet the designer's creative feeling; thus, some descenders may be shorter (or longer) than others. See also <a title="Ascender" href="Ascender">Ascender</a> and <a title="x-Height" href="x-Height">x-Height</a>. 
</p>
